725082f-b.text:
19th Road (O1d Bovery Say Road) north side, between Nineteenth Avenue and 77th Street, showing four views of the Riker -Lent families cemetery. In the background of these views is the Isaac Rapelve farmhouse, History has it that Harck Siehoutsen wettiwd at Poor Bowery about 1658. In 1727 his son Jacobus Krauk (bevd) willed the farm to his nephew Abraham lLent, son of Rvck the eldest son of Abraham Rycken. Daniel Lent, the youngest son of Jacobus who died in 1797, was thhe last of the family who reeided here. In 187O Isaac Rapelve purchased the house. Abraham Rycker, son of the first settler died in 1746 in his 91st year. This inscrition was on his tombstone, whhich Nas standing in 1881. Some members of the family inhumed here are Dr. John Berrien Riker, a personal frierd of Geo. Washirgton and a member of his staff. He was a surgeon during the War of the Revolutiong Captain Abraham Riker who died at Vallev Forge, Waptain Andrew Riker, prominent in the ar of 1812, 1. McKisson, a member of the family of Gov. Geo. Clinton during the Rewoltion and a friend of his vife, Louise de Vallimont, a refuaee of the Prench Revolution, Dr. Wm. James McNevin lIrish patriot chemist and scholar, his wife, and children; amnd John Gampbell Iriah
patriot and philanthropist.
